recordings.loc: Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
recordings.file-name: XC601906-Carolina Wren vocalization in the rain.mp3
recordings.rmk: The fact that is was raining is significant only to the extent that the bird - and only this bird - was active at the time.  I characterize this as 'cheer', produced by the male in response to my presence in the doorway to the garage where I stood with recorder in hand.  Carolina Wrens are notorious for attempting to nest, and post-breeding take shelter, in these openings, so I assume it treated my presence as a predator or a hinderance. This is consistent with researchers' explanation of this vocalization.  That said, this species is apparently known for geographic dialects of this sound  as well as others.

recordings.loc: Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
recordings.rmk: On 5 of 8 days I sneaked a tiny microphone into a hanging basket on my deck where Carolina Wrens had built a nest. I was going to add a sixth day, but they fledged! Throughout the recording you can hear the nestlings rustling around in the leaves and pine straw of the nest. On day 1 they emit a begging call consistently, even without the presence of a parent. Thereafter they remain quiet until the parent signals his or her approach with a single chip note. Each day the begging of two chicks increases in volume. This particularly noticeable in the last segment. There will be a fade of 3 to 5 seconds between days.

recordings.loc: Overgaard senior center, Navajo County, Arizona
recordings.rmk: Same individual as XC295852 and XC295853. Only fourth record of this species for Arizona. Photographs also obtained and submitted for documentation to Arizona Bird Committee. Amplification, low and high pass filters used in Audacity. Bird was first photographed and reported by Jerry Jackson on 14 Dec. 2015. After spending a while waiting at feeders of his nearby residence, I tried playing calls from the Sibley app on my phone and eventually the bird popped up in a weeping willow in a nearby yard and called. The only vocalizations it gave were these "dit, dit-dit" alarm call notes. Snow was on the ground from a recent storm and temperature had been at or below 0 degrees Fahrenheit that morning.

recordings.loc: Tama (near  Burlington), Des Moines, Iowa
recordings.rmk: This was 2 fledgling Carolina Wrens, maybe a few days out of the nest hanging out in a bush.  They were definitely waiting to get fed but I think these were more like alarm calls due to my presence rather than begging calls because there wasn't an adult in the immediate vicinity.

recordings.loc: Tama (near  Burlington), Des Moines, Iowa
recordings.rmk: This bird was singing but as I approached it stopped and hopped to a higher perch and began calling in an agitated fashion for a few minutes.  It settled down once I was still for awhile and it seemed to realize I wasn't an immediate threat.  The bird was maybe 20 ft above me.

recordings.loc: Yard, Croton, New York
recordings.type: alarm call, call, countersinging, female?, male, song
recordings.rmk: To me this is a very interesting recording and I was lucky enough to catch this interaction. One male starts by singing an unusual song strophe, then gives loud "cheer" alarm calls. Another male introduces a more regular song strophe, and the closer bird repeats a variation that is lower in pitch, but otherwise exactly the same. This exact thing happens once more. Each of the males is dueting with a chattering female, and toward the end the closer female starts to give short chatter calls.
